.SH NAME
Linux::Event::Reactor \- Readiness\-based event loop engine for Linux::Event
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&  use v5.36;
\&  use Linux::Event;
\&
\&  my $loop = Linux::Event\->new(
\&    model   => \*(Aqreactor\*(Aq,
\&    backend => \*(Aqepoll\*(Aq,
\&  );
\&
\&  $loop\->after(0.100, sub ($loop) {
\&    say "timer fired";
\&  });
\&
\&  my $watcher = $loop\->watch(
\&    $fh,
\&    read => sub ($loop, $fh, $watcher) {
\&      my $buf = \*(Aq\*(Aq;
\&      my $n = sysread($fh, $buf, 8192);
\&
\&      if (!defined $n) {
\&        die "sysread failed: $!";
\&      }
\&
\&      if ($n == 0) {
\&        $watcher\->cancel;
\&        $loop\->stop;
\&        return;
\&      }
\&
\&      print $buf;
\&    },
\&  );
\&
\&  $loop\->run;
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
\&\f(CW\*(C`Linux::Event::Reactor\*(C'\fR is the readiness engine in this distribution. It is
built around epoll readiness notifications plus Linux\-native primitives for
monotonic timers, signals, wakeups, and pidfds.
.PP
It is deliberately small and explicit:
.IP \(bu 4
it watches filehandles for readiness
.IP \(bu 4
it schedules timers in monotonic time
.IP \(bu 4
it adapts Linux signal, wakeup, and pid primitives into the loop
.IP \(bu 4
it does not own socket acquisition or buffered stream policy
.PP
Higher\-level networking remains in companion distributions such as
Linux::Event::Listen, Linux::Event::Connect, and Linux::Event::Stream.
.SH CONSTRUCTOR
.IX Header "CONSTRUCTOR"
.SS new(%args)
.IX Subsection "new(%args)"
Recognized arguments:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`backend\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Backend name or backend object. The built\-in backend is \f(CW\*(C`epoll\*(C'\fR.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`clock\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Clock object. It must provide \f(CW\*(C`tick\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`now_ns\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`deadline_in_ns\*(C'\fR, and
\&\f(CW\*(C`remaining_ns\*(C'\fR.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`timer\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Timer object. It must provide \f(CW\*(C`after\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`disarm\*(C'\fR, \f(CW\*(C`read_ticks\*(C'\fR, and \f(CW\*(C`fh\*(C'\fR.
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`loop\*(C'\fR
.Sp
Optional public loop facade. This is used internally when the reactor is
constructed by Linux::Event::Loop so callbacks receive the public loop
object rather than the engine object.
.SH LIFECYCLE
.IX Header "LIFECYCLE"
.SS run
.IX Subsection "run"
Enter the event loop and keep running until \f(CW\*(C`stop\*(C'\fR is called.
.SS "run_once($timeout_s = undef)"
.IX Subsection "run_once($timeout_s = undef)"
Advance the loop by one iteration. Due timer callbacks are dispatched first;
then the backend wait is entered if appropriate.
.PP
\&\f(CW$timeout_s\fR is in seconds and may be fractional.
.SS stop
.IX Subsection "stop"
Stop a running loop. If a wakeup object has already been created, the reactor
signals it so a blocking backend wait can return promptly.
.SS is_running
.IX Subsection "is_running"
True while \f(CW\*(C`run\*(C'\fR is actively looping.
.SH TIMERS
.IX Header "TIMERS"
.ie n .SS "after($seconds, $cb)"
.el .SS "after($seconds, \f(CW$cb\fP)"
.IX Subsection "after($seconds, $cb)"
Schedule \f(CW$cb\fR to run after a relative monotonic delay.
.ie n .SS "at($deadline_seconds, $cb)"
.el .SS "at($deadline_seconds, \f(CW$cb\fP)"
.IX Subsection "at($deadline_seconds, $cb)"
Schedule \f(CW$cb\fR for an absolute monotonic deadline expressed in seconds.
.SS cancel($timer_id)
.IX Subsection "cancel($timer_id)"
Cancel a timer previously returned by \f(CW\*(C`after\*(C'\fR or \f(CW\*(C`at\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Timer callbacks are invoked as:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  $cb\->($loop)
.Ve
.SH WATCHERS
.IX Header "WATCHERS"
.ie n .SS "watch($fh, %spec)"
.el .SS "watch($fh, \f(CW%spec\fP)"
.IX Subsection "watch($fh, %spec)"
Register a watcher for a filehandle. Recognized keys in \f(CW%spec\fR:
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`read\*(C'\fR
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`write\*(C'\fR
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`error\*(C'\fR
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`data\*(C'\fR
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`edge_triggered\*(C'\fR
.IP \(bu 4
\&\f(CW\*(C`oneshot\*(C'\fR
.PP
Returns a Linux::Event::Watcher.
.PP
Watcher callbacks receive:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  $cb\->($loop, $fh, $watcher)
.Ve
.PP
The dispatch rules are intentionally explicit:
.IP \(bu 4
error runs first if an error handler is installed and enabled
.IP \(bu 4
otherwise an error condition is treated as readable and writable
.IP \(bu 4
hup also makes the watcher readable so EOF can be observed
.SS unwatch($fh)
.IX Subsection "unwatch($fh)"
Remove the watcher for the given filehandle, if one exists.
.SH "SIGNALS, WAKEUPS, AND PIDFDS"
.IX Header "SIGNALS, WAKEUPS, AND PIDFDS"
.SS signal(...)
.IX Subsection "signal(...)"
Returns the loop\-owned Linux::Event::Signal adaptor and subscribes a signal
handler.
.SS waker
.IX Subsection "waker"
Returns the loop\-owned Linux::Event::Wakeup object. The reactor installs an
internal watcher that drains the eventfd so stop and explicit signals can wake
backend waits promptly.
.SS pid(...)
.IX Subsection "pid(...)"
Returns a pid subscription using the loop\-owned Linux::Event::Pid adaptor.
.SH ACCESSORS
.IX Header "ACCESSORS"
.SS clock
.IX Subsection "clock"
